    "markdown": "# Ch. 2: Tasks & Quizzes {.unnumbered}\n\n::: {.callout-tip collapse=\"false\"}\n#### Your turn! {.unnumbered}\n\nFor these quiz questions and many future tasks, we will make use of the IRIS database.\n\n-   Connect to the [IRIS website](https://iris-database.org/) and navigate to its [Search and Download](https://iris-database.org/search) page.\n-   Scroll down to the filter option 'Data Type'.\n-   Click on 'Data Type' and browse through the different data types that are most commonly used in language-related research.\n\n![Screenshot from the IRIS database search page (accessed on 17 April 2024)](images/IRISDataTypes.png){fig-alt=\"Data Type filter dropdown menu with the following visible categories: Oral production (168), Closed response format (157), Open response (105), Judgements (97), Written production (76), Reaction times (62), Qualitative (46)\" width=\"250\"}\n\n[**Q2.1**]{style=\"color:green;\"} For which kinds of studies could these different types of data have been collected? Think about both experimental and observational studies.\n\n[**Q2.2**]{style=\"color:green;\"} Which of these data types is most likely to be measured in milliseconds (ms)?\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n\n```{=html}\n<form name=\"form_Q2_2\" onsubmit=\"return validate_form_Q2_2()\" method=\"post\">\n<input type=\"text\" placeholder=\"\" name=\"answer_Q2_2\"/>\n<input type=\"submit\" value=\"Check answer\"/>\n<div id=\"result_Q2_2\"></div>\n</form>\n<script>function validate_form_Q2_2() {var x, text; var x = document.forms['form_Q2_2']['answer_Q2_2'].value;if (x == 'Reaction times'|x == 'reaction times'|x == 'Reaction time'|x == 'Reaction Time'|x == 'Reaction Times'|x == 'reaction'|x == 'Reaction'|x == 'reaction time'){text = 'Yes, well done!';} else {text = 'No, check the list of data types on IRIS.';} document.getElementById('result_Q2_2').innerHTML = text; evaluate_final_score(); return false;}function evaluate_final_score(){\n         element = document.getElementById('checkdown_final_score');\n         if(element === null){return false;} else {var element, text, res1;res1 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_2').innerText == 'Yes, well done!';text = res1;element.innerHTML = text;\n         return false;\n         }}</script>\n```\n\n:::\n:::\n\n:::\n::: {.callout-tip collapse=\"false\"}\n#### Your turn! {.unnumbered}\n\n[**Q2.3**]{style=\"color:green;\"} Which other reasons could potentially jeopardise the comparison of test results data from two different groups of pupils?\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n\n```{=html}\n<form name=\"form_Q2_3\" onsubmit=\"return validate_form_Q2_3()\" method=\"post\">\n<label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"answer_Q2_3_1\" value=\"The two groups having different teachers.\"/>\nThe two groups having different teachers.\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"answer_Q2_3_2\" value=\"One group having a classroom decorated with French flags and posters about France.\"/>\nOne group having a classroom decorated with French flags and posters about France.\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"answer_Q2_3_3\" value=\"One group having a higher proportion of pupils with reading difficulties.\"/>\nOne group having a higher proportion of pupils with reading difficulties.\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"answer_Q2_3_4\" value=\"One group having a single native speaker of French, whilst the other has none.\"/>\nOne group having a single native speaker of French, whilst the other has none.\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"answer_Q2_3_5\" value=\"One group having French lessons on Tuesday mornings, the other on Friday afternoons.\"/>\nOne group having French lessons on Tuesday mornings, the other on Friday afternoons.\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"answer_Q2_3_6\" value=\"One group having a higher proportion of pupils from migrant families.\"/>\nOne group having a higher proportion of pupils from migrant families.\n</label>\n<br/>\n<input type=\"submit\" value=\"Check answer\"/>\n<div id=\"result_Q2_3\"></div>\n</form>\n<script>function validate_form_Q2_3() {var text; var x1 = document.getElementById('answer_Q2_3_1'); var x2 = document.getElementById('answer_Q2_3_2'); var x3 = document.getElementById('answer_Q2_3_3'); var x4 = document.getElementById('answer_Q2_3_4'); var x5 = document.getElementById('answer_Q2_3_5'); var x6 = document.getElementById('answer_Q2_3_6'); if (x1.checked == true&x2.checked == true&x3.checked == true&x4.checked == true&x5.checked == true&x6.checked == true){text = 'ThatŌĆÖs right! All of these factors could potentially influence the outcome of this comparison study. <br><br>Can you think of ways to ensure that these factors are controlled for?';} else {text = 'Not quite. There are more reasons.';} document.getElementById('result_Q2_3').innerHTML = text; evaluate_final_score(); return false;}function evaluate_final_score(){\n         element = document.getElementById('checkdown_final_score');\n         if(element === null){return false;} else {var element, text, res1, res2;res1 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_2').innerText == 'Yes, well done!'; res2 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_3').innerText == 'ThatŌĆÖs right! All of these factors could potentially influence the outcome of this comparison study. Can you think of ways to ensure that these factors are controlled for?';text = res1 + res2;element.innerHTML = text;\n         return false;\n         }}</script>\n```\n\n:::\n:::\n\n:::\n::: {.callout-tip collapse=\"false\"}\n#### Your turn! {.unnumbered}\n\n[**Q2.4**]{style=\"color:green;\"} In which format are Microsoft Word files typically saved?\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n\n```{=html}\n<form name=\"form_Q2_4\" onsubmit=\"return validate_form_Q2_4()\" method=\"post\">\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"answer_Q2_4\" id=\"answer_Q2_4_1\" value=\".docx\"/>\n.docx\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"answer_Q2_4\" id=\"answer_Q2_4_2\" value=\".msword\"/>\n.msword\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"answer_Q2_4\" id=\"answer_Q2_4_3\" value=\".odt\"/>\n.odt\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"answer_Q2_4\" id=\"answer_Q2_4_4\" value=\".docs\"/>\n.docs\n</label>\n<br/>\n<input type=\"submit\" value=\"Check answer\"/>\n<div id=\"result_Q2_4\"></div>\n</form>\n<script>function validate_form_Q2_4() {var x, text; var x = document.forms['form_Q2_4']['answer_Q2_4'].value;if (x == '.docx'){text = 'ThatŌĆÖs right! Though older versions of MS Word used the format <code>.doc</code>.';} else {text = 'ThatŌĆÖs incorrect. Do you have a Word file on your computer whose file extension you could check?';} document.getElementById('result_Q2_4').innerHTML = text; evaluate_final_score(); return false;}function evaluate_final_score(){\n         element = document.getElementById('checkdown_final_score');\n         if(element === null){return false;} else {var element, text, res1, res2, res3;res1 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_2').innerText == 'Yes, well done!'; res2 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_3').innerText == 'ThatŌĆÖs right! All of these factors could potentially influence the outcome of this comparison study. Can you think of ways to ensure that these factors are controlled for?'; res3 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_4').innerText == 'ThatŌĆÖs right! Though older versions of MS Word used the format .doc.';text = res1 + res2 + res3;element.innerHTML = text;\n         return false;\n         }}</script>\n```\n\n:::\n:::\n\n\n[**Q2.5**]{style=\"color:green;\"} Which of these files are audio files?\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n\n```{=html}\n<form name=\"form_Q2_5\" onsubmit=\"return validate_form_Q2_5()\" method=\"post\">\n<label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"answer_Q2_5_1\" value=\"001_dialog.flac\"/>\n001_dialog.flac\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"answer_Q2_5_2\" value=\"dialogue001.wav\"/>\ndialogue001.wav\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"answer_Q2_5_3\" value=\"DIALOGUE.audio\"/>\nDIALOGUE.audio\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"answer_Q2_5_4\" value=\"dialogue001.mp3\"/>\ndialogue001.mp3\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"checkbox\" id=\"answer_Q2_5_5\" value=\"dialog_01.csv\"/>\ndialog_01.csv\n</label>\n<br/>\n<input type=\"submit\" value=\"Check answer\"/>\n<div id=\"result_Q2_5\"></div>\n</form>\n<script>function validate_form_Q2_5() {var text; var x1 = document.getElementById('answer_Q2_5_1'); var x2 = document.getElementById('answer_Q2_5_2'); var x3 = document.getElementById('answer_Q2_5_3'); var x4 = document.getElementById('answer_Q2_5_4'); var x5 = document.getElementById('answer_Q2_5_5'); if (x1.checked == true&x2.checked == true&x3.checked == false&x4.checked == true&x5.checked == false){text = 'ThatŌĆÖs right!';} else {text = 'Not quite.';} document.getElementById('result_Q2_5').innerHTML = text; evaluate_final_score(); return false;}function evaluate_final_score(){\n         element = document.getElementById('checkdown_final_score');\n         if(element === null){return false;} else {var element, text, res1;res1 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_5').innerText == 'ThatŌĆÖs right!';text = res1;element.innerHTML = text;\n         return false;\n         }}</script>\n```\n\n:::\n\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n\n```{=html}\n<div id=\"hint_70737\" onclick=\"return show_hint_70737()\">­¤ÉŁ Click on the mouse for a hint.</div>\n<div id=\"result_70737\" onclick=\"return show_hint_70737()\"></div>\n<script>function show_hint_70737(){var x = document.getElementById('result_70737').innerHTML; if(!x){document.getElementById('result_70737').innerHTML = 'There are three audio files in this list.';} else {document.getElementById('result_70737').innerHTML = '';}}</script>\n```\n\n:::\n:::\n\n:::\n::: {.callout-tip collapse=\"false\"}\n#### Your turn! {.unnumbered}\n\nImagine that you want to run an experiment similar to the one carried out in @schimkeFirstLanguageInfluence2018. You can reuse the Playmobil image files created by the researchers as they helpfully uploaded them to the IRIS database.\n\nIn which file format do you think the images are archived? To find out, click [here](https://iris-database.org/search/?s_publicationAPAInlineReference=Schimke%20et%20al.%20(2018)) to go directly to the list of data and materials associated with the study. There are four entries in the IRIS database that are associated with this study. Select the \"Pictorial\" entry which contains the images. It allows you to download a ZIP file called `Images_online.zip`. ZIP is an archive file format that can contain one or more compressed files. Download this ZIP file and decompress ('unzip') it. You should find that it contains a folder entitled 'Images', which contains 58 pictures of different combinations of Playmobil figures that correspond to the experiment's stimulus sentences.\n\n[**Q2.6**]{style=\"color:green;\"} In which file format are these Playmobil image files?\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n\n```{=html}\n<form name=\"form_Q2_6\" onsubmit=\"return validate_form_Q2_6()\" method=\"post\">\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"answer_Q2_6\" id=\"answer_Q2_6_1\" value=\"BMP\"/>\nBMP\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"answer_Q2_6\" id=\"answer_Q2_6_2\" value=\"GIMP\"/>\nGIMP\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"answer_Q2_6\" id=\"answer_Q2_6_3\" value=\"JPEG\"/>\nJPEG\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"answer_Q2_6\" id=\"answer_Q2_6_4\" value=\"PNG\"/>\nPNG\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"answer_Q2_6\" id=\"answer_Q2_6_5\" value=\"GIF\"/>\nGIF\n</label>\n<br/>\n<input type=\"submit\" value=\"Check answer\"/>\n<div id=\"result_Q2_6\"></div>\n</form>\n<script>function validate_form_Q2_6() {var x, text; var x = document.forms['form_Q2_6']['answer_Q2_6'].value;if (x == 'BMP'){text = 'ThatŌĆÖs right!';} else {text = 'This is an image file format, but these Playmobil images are not saved in this format.';} document.getElementById('result_Q2_6').innerHTML = text; evaluate_final_score(); return false;}function evaluate_final_score(){\n         element = document.getElementById('checkdown_final_score');\n         if(element === null){return false;} else {var element, text, res1, res2, res3, res4, res5;res1 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_2').innerText == 'Yes, well done!'; res2 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_3').innerText == 'ThatŌĆÖs right! All of these factors could potentially influence the outcome of this comparison study. Can you think of ways to ensure that these factors are controlled for?'; res3 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_4').innerText == 'ThatŌĆÖs right! Though older versions of MS Word used the format .doc.'; res4 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_5').innerText == 'ThatŌĆÖs right!'; res5 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_6').innerText == 'ThatŌĆÖs right!';text = res1 + res2 + res3 + res4 + res5;element.innerHTML = text;\n         return false;\n         }}</script>\n```\n\n:::\n:::\n\n\nImage files typically contain metadata that is embedded in the image files themselves. This metadata may include the dimensions of the image and its colour profile. To view this metadata, right-click on one of the image files that you have extracted from the ZIP file and select the option to get more information about the file, e.g. \"Get Info\" or \"Properties\".\n\n[**Q2.7**]{style=\"color:green;\"} How wide are these Playmobil images in pixel?\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n\n```{=html}\n<form name=\"form_Q2_7\" onsubmit=\"return validate_form_Q2_7()\" method=\"post\">\n<input type=\"text\" placeholder=\"\" name=\"answer_Q2_7\"/>\n<input type=\"submit\" value=\"Check answer\"/>\n<div id=\"result_Q2_7\"></div>\n</form>\n<script>function validate_form_Q2_7() {var x, text; var x = document.forms['form_Q2_7']['answer_Q2_7'].value;if (x == '1024'){text = 'ThatŌĆÖs right, well done!';} else {text = 'No. Image dimensions are usually displayed as two numbers separated by an ŌĆ£xŌĆØ symbol. As these Playmobil images are all in landscape format so that the larger number corresponds to the width of the images.';} document.getElementById('result_Q2_7').innerHTML = text; evaluate_final_score(); return false;}function evaluate_final_score(){\n         element = document.getElementById('checkdown_final_score');\n         if(element === null){return false;} else {var element, text, res1, res2, res3, res4, res5, res6;res1 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_2').innerText == 'Yes, well done!'; res2 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_3').innerText == 'ThatŌĆÖs right! All of these factors could potentially influence the outcome of this comparison study. Can you think of ways to ensure that these factors are controlled for?'; res3 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_4').innerText == 'ThatŌĆÖs right! Though older versions of MS Word used the format .doc.'; res4 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_5').innerText == 'ThatŌĆÖs right!'; res5 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_6').innerText == 'ThatŌĆÖs right!'; res6 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_7').innerText == 'ThatŌĆÖs right, well done!';text = res1 + res2 + res3 + res4 + res5 + res6;element.innerHTML = text;\n         return false;\n         }}</script>\n```\n\n:::\n:::\n\n:::\n::: {.callout-tip collapse=\"false\"}\n#### Your turn! {.unnumbered}\n\nIn this [**task**]{style=\"color:green;\"}, we will practice opening a DSV file in LibreOffice Calc. Our example file is a real dataset from @schimkeFirstLanguageInfluence2018. We will begin by downloading it from the public repository [IRIS](https://iris-database.org/search/?s_publicationAPAInlineReference=Schimke%20et%20al.%20(2018)).\n\nIn addition to the eye-tracking experiments, @schimkeFirstLanguageInfluence2018 conducted two further experiments in which participants completed a gap-filling task via an online survey platform. In the first of these experiments, the participants were native (L1) speakers of French, German, and Spanish. In the second, they were French- and Spanish-speaking learners (L2) of German.\n\nIn both experiments, the L1 and L2 participants were shown ambiguous sentences similar to the ones used in the eye-tracking experiment with the Playmobil images (see @nte-Eyetracking). After having read each stimulus, the participants were asked to complete a gap-fill task according to their understanding of the preceding ambiguous sentence. Participants were told \"that there were no incorrect responses and that they should answer spontaneously\" [@schimkeFirstLanguageInfluence2018: 755]. Below is an example questionnaire item in the three languages examined:\n\n<div>\n\n> 1\\. *Der Brieftr├żger ist dem Stra├¤enfeger begegnet, bevor er schnell ein Sandwich geholt hat. \\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_ hat ein Sandwich geholt.*\n>\n> 2\\. *Le facteur a rencontr├® le balayeur avant qu'il prenne rapidement un sandwich. \\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_ a pris un sandwich.*\n>\n> *3a. El cartero se reuni├│ con el barrendero antes de que ├®l recogiera velozmente un emparedado. \\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_ recogi├│ un emparedado.*\n>\n> 3b. *El cartero se reuni├│ con el barrendero antes de que recogiera velozmente un emparedado. \\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_ recogi├│ un emparedado.*\n\n</div>\n\nNote that, for Spanish, there were two types of stimuli: one with an overt pronoun (as in 3a. with *├®l*) and one without (as in 3b. with a null pronoun), as both variants are possible in Spanish. All three examples translate as:\n\n> -   *The postman encountered the street sweeper before he quickly fetched a sandwich. \\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_\\_ fetched a sandwich.*\n\nTo complete the gap, participants could either select 'The postman' or 'The street sweeper'.\n\n1.  Go back to the study's page on [IRIS](https://iris-database.org/search/?s_publicationAPAInlineReference=Schimke%20et%20al.%20(2018)) and select the second entry entitled 'Other questionnaire' which, among other things, contains 'Written production data'.\n\nNote that this database entry includes both research data and research materials: the file `sentences_offline_task.xlsx` contains the full list of questionnaire items, including both experimental and filler items, with which we could reconstruct the experiment to replicate it with a new set of participants. For now, however, we are not interested in obtaining materials to replicate the study, but rather in examining the study's original data.\n\nThis [IRIS entry](https://iris-database.org/details/lYT9m-a75tV) also contains three data files. The last file (`logoddslearnersfinal.txt`) is the DSV file that was used to create @tbl-EyeTrackingTable above.\n\nIn this [**task**]{style=\"color:green;\"}, we are going to look at the questionnaire data corresponding to the gap-filling task experiment conducted with German L2 learners, which is contained in the data file `offlinedataLearners.txt`:\n\n2.  Download the `offlinedataLearners.txt` file (which is the second listed) and save it on your computer (see @sec-FoldersPaths).\n3.  Launch LibreOffice (see @sec-OpenSource if you have not yet installed LibreOffice) and, from the list of options under 'Create', click on 'Calc Spreadsheet' to open up a blank spreadsheet.\n4.  From the 'File' drop-down menu, select 'Open...' or use the keyboard shortcut 'Ctrl/Cmd + O'. Find `offlinedataLearners.txt` in the folder where you saved it and click on 'Open'.\n5.  A 'Text Import' dialogue box will pop up. This a DSV file, not a fixed-width file, so ensure that the option 'Separated by' is selected. If not already set by default, it is also a good idea to select 'Unicode (UTF-8)' for the 'Character set'.\n6.  Experiment with the different 'Separator Options' until the preview at the bottom of the dialogue box looks like a table.\n7.  Ensure that, apart from the 'Separator Options', all other options in the dialogue box are unselected and then click on 'OK'.\n\n[**Q2.8**]{style=\"color:green;\"} What is the separator character in the file `offlinedataLearners.txt`?\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n\n```{=html}\n<form name=\"form_Q2_8\" onsubmit=\"return validate_form_Q2_8()\" method=\"post\">\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"answer_Q2_8\" id=\"answer_Q2_8_1\" value=\"Tab\"/>\nTab\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"answer_Q2_8\" id=\"answer_Q2_8_2\" value=\"Comma\"/>\nComma\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"answer_Q2_8\" id=\"answer_Q2_8_3\" value=\"Semicolon\"/>\nSemicolon\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"answer_Q2_8\" id=\"answer_Q2_8_4\" value=\"Space\"/>\nSpace\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"answer_Q2_8\" id=\"answer_Q2_8_5\" value=\"All of them\"/>\nAll of them\n</label>\n<br/>\n<input type=\"submit\" value=\"Check answer\"/>\n<div id=\"result_Q2_8\"></div>\n</form>\n<script>function validate_form_Q2_8() {var x, text; var x = document.forms['form_Q2_8']['answer_Q2_8'].value;if (x == 'Tab'){text = 'ThatŌĆÖs right!';} else {text = 'ThatŌĆÖs incorrect. Try selecting the other separators options in the ŌĆ£Text ImportŌĆØ dialogue box until the preview of the table looks like a table.';} document.getElementById('result_Q2_8').innerHTML = text; evaluate_final_score(); return false;}function evaluate_final_score(){\n         element = document.getElementById('checkdown_final_score');\n         if(element === null){return false;} else {var element, text, res1, res2, res3, res4, res5, res6, res7;res1 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_2').innerText == 'Yes, well done!'; res2 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_3').innerText == 'ThatŌĆÖs right! All of these factors could potentially influence the outcome of this comparison study. Can you think of ways to ensure that these factors are controlled for?'; res3 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_4').innerText == 'ThatŌĆÖs right! Though older versions of MS Word used the format .doc.'; res4 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_5').innerText == 'ThatŌĆÖs right!'; res5 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_6').innerText == 'ThatŌĆÖs right!'; res6 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_7').innerText == 'ThatŌĆÖs right, well done!'; res7 = document.getElementById('result_Q2_8').innerText == 'ThatŌĆÖs right!';text = res1 + res2 + res3 + res4 + res5 + res6 + res7;element.innerHTML = text;\n         return false;\n         }}</script>\n```\n\n:::\n:::\n\n\n[**Q2.9**]{style=\"color:green;\"} What is the delimiter character in the file `offlinedataLearners.txt`?\n\n\n::: {.cell}\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n\n```{=html}\n<form name=\"form_Q2_9\" onsubmit=\"return validate_form_Q2_9()\" method=\"post\">\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"answer_Q2_9\" id=\"answer_Q2_9_1\" value=\"&quot;\"/>\n\"\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"answer_Q2_9\" id=\"answer_Q2_9_2\" value=\"There is none.\"/>\nThere is none.\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"answer_Q2_9\" id=\"answer_Q2_9_3\" value=\"Both &quot; and &#39;\"/>\nBoth \" and '\n</label>\n<br/>\n<label>\n<input type=\"radio\" name=\"answer_Q2_9\" id=\"answer_Q2_9_4\" value=\"&#39;\"/>\n'\n</label>\n<br/>\n<input type=\"submit\" value=\"Check answer\"/>\n<div id=\"result_Q2_9\"></div>\n</form>\n<script>function validate_form_Q2_9() {var x, text; var x = document.forms['form_Q2_9']['answer_Q2_9'].value;if (x == 'There is none.'){text = 'ThatŌĆÖs right! This particular DSV file does not use a string delimiter.';} else {text = 'Not quite. Try opening the file in a plain-text editor or text-processing program to find out.';} document.getElementById('result_Q2_9').inn